DE LEGATIS.

ξ 216. Α bequest by preception is in the following form: ‘ Let Lucius Titius take my slave Stichus by preception [before partition].'

ξ 217. My school hold that such a bequest can only be made to one of several coheirs, because precep- tion, or previous taking, can only be attributed to a person wh0‚ taking as heir, over and above his por- tion as heir, and before partition of the inheritance between the coheirs, takes something as legates.

ξ 218. Therefore, if a stranger have a legacy in this form it is void, and Sabinus held that the flaw is not remedied by the senatusconsult of Nem, for that senatusconsult only cures verbal flaws which make a bequest informal at civil law, not personal disabilities of the legatee. Julian, however, and Sextus held that this bequest also is made valid by the senatusconsult‚ as only being avoided at civil law by a verbal informality, as appears from the fact that the very same person might take by a bequest in another form, for instance, the form of per- mission‚ whereas personal disability of a legatee implies inability to take under any form, as that of an alien, who wants testamentifactio passiva, and is not relieved by the senatusconsult.

ᾗ 219. Again, my school hold that in this form of bequest, the only action by vihich a legates can recover is the action for partition of an inheritance, the judge's commis· sion including a power of adjudi- cating a thing bequeathed by pre- ception.
